{"cursor":"34893","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox language |name=Old Latin |nativename= |region=Italy |states=Roman\nRepublic |nation=Rome |script=Latin alphabetÂ  |era=Developed into Classical Latin in 1st\ncentury BC |imagecaption=Titus Maccius Plautus, an Old Latin writer |image=Tito\nMaccio Plauto.jpg |map=Expansion of Rome, 2nd century BC.gif\n|mapcaption=Expansion of the Roman Republic, 2nd century BC. It is unlikely\nLatin was spoken much beyond the green area, and was by no means ubiquitous\nwithin it. |agency= Schools of grammar and rhetoric |familycolor=Indo-European\n|fam2=Italic |fam3=Latino-Faliscan |fam4=Latin |iso3= |isoexception=historical\n|linglist=qbb |notice=IPA }} 'Old Latin' (also called 'Early Latin' or 'Archaic\nLatin') refers to the Latin language in the period before the age of Classical\nLatin; that is, all Latin before 75 BC. The term 'prisca Latinitas'\ndistinguishes it in New Latin and Contemporary Latin from vetus Latina, in which\n\"old\" has another meaning.\n\nThe use of \"old\", \"early\" and \"archaic\" has been standard in publications of the\ncorpus of Old Latin writings since at least the 18th century. The definition is\nnot arbitrary but these terms refer to writings with spelling conventions and\nword forms not generally found in works written under the Roman Empire. This\narticle presents some of the major differences.\n","linknr":656,"url":"Old_Latin","recorded":1362373252,"links":29,"instances":["poetry","consul_129_bc","mythology","linguistics","consul_259_bc","poet"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Ancient Rome","Latin language"],"headings":["Philological constructs","Corpus","Script","Orthography","Phonology","Grammar and morphology","Bibliography","Sources","See also","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/95/Tito_Maccio_Plauto.jpg/200px-Tito_Maccio_Plauto.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Expansion_of_Rome%2C_2nd_century_BC.gif/300px-